Jakarta Grab Data Analysis

Get Dataset for Hour Distribution

We first store the date, day of the week and hours of the day where each trj_id occurs into the variable hourdistr.

#Add time column in WIB 
jkt_data_with_time<- jkt_data%>%
  mutate(time = as_datetime(pingtimestamp))%>%
  mutate(time = with_tz(time, tzone = "Asia/Jakarta"))

#Hour distribution
days_of_week<- c("Monday", "Tuesday", "Wednesday", "Thursday", "Friday", "Saturday", "Sunday")
hourdist<- jkt_data_with_time%>% 
  mutate(hour = hour(time), day_of_week = weekdays(time), day = day(time))%>%
  mutate(day_of_week = factor(day_of_week, levels = days_of_week))%>%
  distinct(trj_id, hour, day_of_week, day)

Overall distribution of trips by hour

ggplot(hourdist)+
  geom_histogram(aes(hour, y = ..density..), binwidth = 1, color = "white", fill = "blueviolet")+
  labs(title = "Distribution of trips by hour", x = "Hour", y = "Density")

By looking at the distribution of trips in every hour, we can see that there is a peak around 4-5pm in the evening. Hence, there are higher demand for grab rides during these hours.

High Inaccuracy Areas

jkt_data%>%
  filter(accuracy>=200)%>%
  leaflet()%>%
  addTiles()%>%
  addCircleMarkers(lat = ~rawlat, lng= ~rawlng, color = "blueviolet",fillColor = "blueviolet", opacity = 0.05, fillOpacity = 0.1)

We also analyse the regions where pings had higher inaccuracies. As we can see on the plot, most of the inaccuracies tend to occur along this highway. Other inaccuracies can also be seen around the central area of Jakarta. Particularly along the junctions when the main road meets the highway. Finally we also see a cluster around Bogor and Karawang.

Distribution of trips by hour, by day of the week

ggplot(hourdist)+
  geom_histogram(aes(hour), binwidth=1, color = "white", fill = "blueviolet")+
  labs(title = "Distribution of trips by hour each day of the week", x = "Hour", y = "Count")+
  facet_wrap(~day_of_week)

When we look at the distribution of trips by day of the week, we can see a few trends. Firstly, there is a large number of trips specifically at 6pm on Thursdays. There also seems to be some spike in the demand on weekday evening hours (4-5pm) as well as during Saturday afternoon hours (1-2pm).

Possible impact of Election & Good Friday

hols<- c(12,19,10,17)
labels_hols<- c("12" = "12 April 2019", "19" = "19 April 2019 (Good Friday)", "10" = "10 April 2019", "17" = "17 April 2019 (Presidential Election)")

hourdist%>%
  filter(day %in% hols)%>%
  mutate(day = factor(day, levels = hols))%>%
  ggplot()+
  geom_histogram(aes(hour), binwidth = 1, color = "white", fill = "blueviolet")+
  labs(title = "Distribution of trips by hour on 2 different Wednesdays and Fridays", y = "Count", x= "Hour")+
  facet_wrap(~day, labeller = as_labeller(labels_hols), nrow = 1)

Out of the 2 Fridays in the data, 19 April 2019 is a Good Friday public holiday. We compare the distribution by hour on 19 April with the distribution on 12 April. The plot shows that aggregate demand on Good Friday is higher. The rise/spike in data occurs much later in the day on Good Friday (after 10 am), and peaks around 1-5pm.

Possible impact of weather

weathers<- c(11,18)
labels_weather<- c("11" = "11 April 2019", "18" = "18 April 2019")

hourdist%>%
  filter(day %in% weathers)%>%
  ggplot()+
  geom_histogram(aes(hour), binwidth = 1, color = "white", fill = "blueviolet")+
  labs(title = "Distribution of trips by hour for different weathers", y = "Count", x= "Hour")+
  facet_wrap(~day, labeller = as_labeller(labels_weather), nrow = 1)

Between the 2 Thursdays in our data, 11 April had a regular weather, with some haze before 9am in the morning while 18 April had thunderstorm 2-7pm. Although the demands in both days spike in evening hours, the demand on 18 April, 3-6pm is nearly double than the demand on 11 April evening hours.

Final thoughts

As we are only using 2 weeks worth of data, our observations are very sensitive to outliers and it may be difficult to draw any concrete conclusions. However, we can use similar data analysis on more data that we gather to see if the trends we identified hold over a larger set of data, which would mean that they are more likely to be statistically significant. For instance, we can look to see if the trend of greater demand on Thursday 6pm holds over more weeks, or if the average demand during periods with thunderstorm is greater than when the weather is fine.
